	<h1 style="margin: 10px 0px; font:bold 52px/65px 'Ruda',arial; text-align: left;">10 clicks to the incredible Mr. Mandela</h1>
    <h3 style="margin: 10px 0px;font: 20px/22px 'Ruda',arial;">Click on the bands and discover incredible facts you did not know about Nelson Mandela
 </h3>
    </section>
     <div class="clear"></div>
   
<div class="clear"></div>
<div class="container">

<div class="box-a lft">
<div class="popcont" action="boxone">
	<div class="caption"><span>Stylish Rebel </span>
    <div class="popbox" style="display:none">
    <ul>
		<li>Mandela's father Hendry Mandela, an African chieftain, had four wives. Mandela was born of the third wife.</li>
		<li>When Mandela was 9, his father died leaving him under the care of Thembu king Jongintaba Dalindyebo.</li>
		<li>Mandela was expelled from University College for protesting against bad quality of food (1940).</li>
		<li>Mandela ran away to Johannesburg after he found that his marriage was fixed to a 'fat' girl who loved someone else. </li>
		<li>Initially, Mandela worked at a mine in Johannesburg as a night watchman. </li>
		<li>Young Mandela loved boxing, sparring ninety minutes in a gym.</li>
		<li>When his legal practice took off, Mandela loved to dress smart & drove around in an Oldsmobile.</li>

    </ul>
    </div>
    </div></div>
</div>
<div class="box-b lft">
<div class="popcont" action="boxtwo">
	<div class="caption"><span>Sheep & shirts </span>
    <div class="popbox" style="display:none">
    <ul>
    	<li>Mandela loved gardening, which he picked up in prison. </li>
		<li>The colourful Batik shirts that Mandela wore (popularly known as Madiba shirts) are of Javanese origin. </li>
		<li>Mandela's favourite food was the meat of a slaughtered sheep, watered down with a bowl of Amarhewu. Amarhewu is a fermented meal drink with a sour taste.</li>
    </ul>
    </div>
    </div></div>
</div>
<div class="box-c lft">
	<div class="popcont" action="boxthree">
	<div class="caption"><span>Hollywood's Muse </span>
    <div class="popbox" style="display:none">
   <p> <strong>Invictus (2009):</strong> Starring Morgan Freeman as Mandela, Invictus is the story of Mandela's attempt to unite South Africa by inspiring the rugby team to win the 1994 world cup.</p>
<p><strong>Goodbye Bafana (2007):</strong> A white South African racist is given the job of guarding Nelson Mandela. Goodbye Bafana is the story of how their association changes the guard's worldview </p>
<p><strong>Mandela and de Klerk (1997):</strong> Sidney Poitier played Mandela and Michael Caine played South African President FW de Klerk. Need we say more? </p>

    </div>
    </div></div>
</div>
<div class="box-d lft">
	<div class="popcont" action="boxfour">
	<div class="caption"><span>Words of Wisdom </span>
    <div class="popbox" style="display:none">
    <ul>
    	<li>"It always seems impossible until it's done."</li>
		<li>"In my country we go to prison first and then become President."</li>
		<li>"It is wise to persuade people to do things and make them think it was their own idea."</li>
<li>"I learned that courage was not the absence of fear, but the triumph over it. The brave man is not he who does not feel afraid, but he who conquers that fear."</li>
   </ul>
    </div>
    </div></div>
</div>
<div class="box-e lft">
	<div class="popcont" action="boxfive">
	<div class="caption"><span>Mandela & India </span>
    <div class="popbox" style="display:none">
    <ul>
    	<li>Mandela extensively 'borrowed' from Nehru's speeches. "I used a lot of writing of Nehru without acknowledging it, which was a silly thing to do. But when there is a paucity of views in you, you are inclined to do that," said Mandela.</li>
		<li>India was among the first countries to accord the African National Congress diplomatic status in 1967. </li>
		<li>Nelson Mandela reciprocated by choosing India as the first country to visit after his release from prison. </li>
    </ul>
    </div>
    </div></div>
</div>

<div class="box-f lft">
	<div class="popcont" action="boxsix">
	<div class="caption"><span>Fighter, Prisoner </span>
    <div class="popbox" style="display:none">
    <ul>
    	<li>Mandela spent 27 years in prison - 18 of which were spent in Robben Island. His cell was 8X8 ft in size, he was prisoner 46664. </li>
		<li>Mandela slept on the floor, he had a bucket for a toilet & was forced to do hard labour in a quarry.</li>
		<li>Mandela was not allowed to attend the funerals of his mother & his son who died during his prison sentence.</li>
		<li>American President Ronald Reagan's administration labelled the ANC a terrorist organisation.</li>
    </ul>
    </div>
    </div></div>
</div>
<div class="box-g lft">
	<div class="popcont" action="boxseven">
	<div class="caption"><span>Mandela, the lover</span>
    <div class="popbox" style="display:none">
    <p>From prison, Mandela wrote passionate letters to his second wife, Winnie Mandela.  Excerpts:</p>
 <ul>
	 <li> " Your beautiful photo still stands about two feet above my left shoulder as I write this note. I dust it carefully every morning, for to do so gives me the pleasant feeling that I'm caressing you as in the old days. " - Letter dated April, 1976</li> 

	<li>"Letters from you and the family are like the arrival of summer rains and spring that liven my life and make it enjoyable. Whenever I write you, I feel that inside physical warmth, that makes me forget all my problems." - Letter dated, October, 1976</li>    
    </ul>
    	
    </div>
    </div></div>
</div>
<div class="box-h lft">


	<div class="popcont" action="boxeight">
    <div class="caption"><span>Mandela's many names</span>
    <div class="popbox" style="display:none">
    <ul>
    	<li><strong>Rolihlahla:</strong> Mandela's birth name in isiXhosa, an African language. Colloquially, it means "troublemaker".</li>
		<li><strong>Nelson:</strong> Mandela's teacher Miss Mdingane gave him this name. Giving African children English names was a custom initiated by British colonials.</li>
		<li><strong>Madiba:</strong> The name of the clan Mandela belongs to. Madiba was the name of a 18th century Thembu chief.</li>
		<li><strong>Tata:</strong> Means "father" and is a term of endearment used by South Africans for Mandela.</li>
		<li><strong>Khulu:</strong> Means great, paramount, grand. Mandela is often addressed as Khulu. </li>
